            <note>Ms. leaves.</note>
            <note>Title supplied by cataloger (Zacour-Hirsch).</note>
            <note>Layout: Main text written in 2 columns of 50-52 lines; commentary text written in 2 columns of 90-109 lines; horizontal and vertical bounding lines ruled in lead.</note>
            <note>Script: Written in a Gothic script.</note>
            <note>Decoration: Initials (1-line to 3-line) alternating in red and blue ink, paragraph marks in red and blue ink, six-line Title 8 initial in red and blue ink.</note>
            <note>Binding: Modern boards.</note>
            <note>Origin: Probably written in France in the 15th century (Zacour-Hirsch).</note>
         </notesStmt>
         <sourceDesc>
            <msDesc>
               <msIdentifier>
                  <settlement>Philadelphia</settlement>
                  <institution>University of Pennsylvania</institution>
                  <repository>Rare Book & Manuscript Library</repository>
                  <idno type="call-number">Ms. Codex 1223</idno>
                  <altIdentifier type="bibid">
                     <idno>4350977</idno>
                  </altIdentifier>
               </msIdentifier>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Bifolium with fragments from Book 37 of the Digests of Justinian I (Byzantine emperor, 527-565), containing (in order) sections of Title 7 on dowries, Title 9 on inheritance, and Title 8 on the children of marriages in which one partner is an emancipated slave. The text is surrounded by 15th-century commentary on the laws.</summary>
                  <textLang>Latin.</textLang>
                  <msItem>
                     <title>Fragments of the Digests of Justinian, Book 37, Titles 7-9</title>
                     <author>Justinian I, Emperor of the East, 483?-565</author>
                     <respStmt>
                        <resp>former owner</resp>
                        <persName>Baugh, Albert C. 1891-1981</persName>
                     </respStmt>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="1r">
                     <locus>1r</locus>
                     <title>De dotis collatione (37.7.1.4), f. 1r</title>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="1v">
                     <locus>1v</locus>
                     <title>De ventre in possessionem mittendo et curatore eius (37.9.1), f. 1v</title>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2r">
                     <locus>2r</locus>
                     <title>De coniungendis cum emancipato liberis eius (37.8.1.10), f. 2r</title>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>

                            </licence>
            </availability>
         </publicationStmt>
         <notesStmt>
            <note>Ms. codex.</note>
            <note>Title supplied by cataloger.</note>
            <note>Collation: Paper, 131; 1⁶(-1) 2¹⁰ 3⁶ 4¹⁰ 5⁶ 6¹⁰ 7-9⁶ 10¹⁰(-1) 11-13⁸ 14⁸(+1) 15⁸(-2) 16¹⁰ 17⁸; contemporary foliation in red ink, upper center recto, 1-5, 7, 6, 8-53, 53--66, [67], 68-76, 78-94, [i], 95-96 (=f. 2-98); modern foliation in pencil, [v, 1-126], upper right recto. References in this record are to modern foliation. Catchwords on almost every page, lower right recto or verso.</note>
            <note>Layout: Written in 2 columns of 27 lines (f. 2r-95v) and 2 columns of 6 staves (f. 97v-107v); frame-ruled in red ink with text ruled in lead.</note>
            <note>Script: Written in a German Gothic script by Georg Keysser (f. 96r).</note>
            <note>Decoration: 3 full-page borders in colored inks with architectural columns (f. 1v, 54v, 69v); 5-line initial and full scrollwork border in colored inks (f. 2r); 8-line initial in colored inks and first words in display uncials in red ink (f. 84v); 2-line initial in 2 colors and knotwork design in colored inks (f. 96r); 1- to 3-line initials in various colors throughout; rubrication, foliation, and frame-ruling in red ink.</note>
            <note>Music: Contains Hufnagelschrift notation on 5-line staves in the Office of the Dead (f. 97r-107v), with later additions in square notation on 4-line staves (f. 108r-108v).</note>
            <note>Binding: Original 16th-century vellum over pasteboard, gold-stamped with stamps of the Annunciation (upper cover) and the Nativity (lower cover) and gold-tooled borders; remnants of 2 pairs of ties.</note>
            <note>Origin: Written in the Benedictine abbey in Elchingen (Bavaria), in 1596 (f. 96r).</note>
         </notesStmt>
         <sourceDesc>
            <msDesc>
               <msIdentifier>
                  <settlement>Philadelphia</settlement>

                     <idno>4936653</idno>
                  </altIdentifier>
               </msIdentifier>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Benedictine manuscript containing texts for Matins and Lauds from the Commemorative Office of the Virgin. This version of the Office was said most often on Saturday in place of the usual Office of the day. Also contains the Office of the Dead accompanied by musical notation for the chants. The manuscript once had leather finding tabs flush to the edge of the leaves, all but one (f. 96) of which have been torn out (for example, f. 1, 7, 69).</summary>

                  <msItem>
